    "recap_headline": "Florida Atlantic University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "BOCA RATON, Fla. \u00a0\u2013\nFlorida Atlantic baseball (14-9, 1-1) evened the weekend series with UTSA (16-7, 1-1) on Saturday, slipping by the Roadrunners for a hard-fought 7-6 victory. Sunday's finale will determine who exits the first American Conference weekend with a 2-1 record in league play.\nTHE BEGINNING\nUTSA jumped in front with a two-run home run in the top of the first, but the Owls responded with three in the bottom of the inning. After a pair of walks,\nPatrick Ward\nlined a two-out, two-RBI double down the right field line to tie the game.\nBrett Patten\nfollowed with a base hit to put the home side ahead by a run.\nMichael Perazza\nand\nKyle Boylston\nchipped in RBI singles in the second and fourth innings to put the Owls up 5-2.\nTHE TURNING POINT\nRedshirt sophomore starter\nKide Adetuyi\nput together another stellar start for Florida Atlantic. After the home run in the first inning and a double by the next batter, Adetuyi did not allow another hit. He departed after five, and the Roadrunners jumped on the FAU bullpen. A walk and three doubles in the sixth added up to a four-run frame to put UTSA back on top 6-5.\nThe Owls tied the game again in the ensuing half inning.\nTJ Gramesty\nled off with his second double of the game and eventually came home on a ground ball to short off the bat of Boylston.\nUTSA loaded the bases with no outs in the seventh before fifth-year senior\nBryan Boully\nentered and slammed the door. A strikeout, a force-out at home, and a ground ball to short ended the threat with the game still tied.\nTHE FINISH\nThe Roadrunners had another chance to take the lead in the eighth. With a runner on first and one out, Boully had to be removed from the game due to injury. Freshman\nBrody Juntunen\ncame on and retired UTSA's Lane Haworth on one pitch. The Owls went back to the bullpen for the next hitter, and\nCarson Kimball\nfollowed suit, inducing a groundout to third base to once again maintain the tie.\nThe Owls took a 7-6 lead in the bottom of the eighth after Patten led off with a single, stole second, moved to third on a sacrifice bunt, and scored the go-ahead run on a passed ball.\nKimball remained on the for the ninth and set the Roadrunners down in order, picking up two strikeouts along the way to seal the victory.\nQUOTABLE\nHead Coach\nJohn McCormack\nPostgame with\n@FAUCoachMac\n#WIP\n\ud83c\udfdd\ufe0f\npic.twitter.com/Q9VilKvHrP\n\u2014 Florida Atlantic Baseball (@FAUBaseball)\nMarch 21, 2026\nTHE BATS\nThe Owls out-hit UTSA 11-8, led by a 3-for-4 day from Patten.\nGramesty finished 2-for-4 with a pair of doubles.\nBoylston went 2-for-4 with two RBI, a run scored, and a stolen base.\nMarshall Lipsey\nsingled twice and stole his team-leading 10th base of the season.\nTHE ARMS\nAdetuyi struck out nine in five innings. He walked three and allowed three hits.\nKimball retired all four batters he faced to earn his first win of the season.\nWHAT'S NEXT\nThe rubber game is set for a 12:05 p.m. first pitch on Sunday at the FAU Baseball Stadium.\nFOLLOW THE OWLS\nTo stay up to date on all things Florida Atlantic baseball, follow us on social media @faubaseball.",
